1
00:06:26,286 --> 00:06:28,148
[SPEAKER_06]: Hello, I'm Zeina Badawi.

2
00:06:28,308 --> 00:06:34,534
[SPEAKER_06]: Welcome to the Maison de la Paix in Geneva for this UN Secretary-General debate.

3
00:06:34,995 --> 00:06:49,530
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, of course, Geneva is a city which is home to numerous UN bodies, so there is a lot of buzz in the city about who is going to be the next Secretary-General of the United Nations, who will succeed Antonio Guterres at the start of the year.

4
00:06:49,930 --> 00:06:52,371
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, currently there are five candidates.

5
00:06:52,872 --> 00:06:54,732
[SPEAKER_06]: Three of them are with me here on stage.

6
00:06:54,773 --> 00:06:57,314
[SPEAKER_06]: We have a video intervention from the fourth.

7
00:06:57,774 --> 00:07:14,622
[SPEAKER_06]: So we're going to be testing their suitability by asking them questions from our audience here about whether they are really the right person to take on this enormous role at a critical time, not only for the UN itself, but at a time in global history.

8
00:07:15,143 --> 00:07:19,465
[SPEAKER_06]: Before we hear from the candidates, we're going to set the scene with this brief film.

9
00:07:26,582 --> 00:07:39,225
[SPEAKER_06]: More than 80 years after its founding, the question of who leads the United Nations is more important than ever before because in 2026, the global order is at a decisive moment.

10
00:07:40,365 --> 00:07:54,529
[SPEAKER_06]: There's not only a series of protracted conflicts which scar the world, but there's also a growing distrust in global institutions and a weakening of the multilateral consensus that has held since the Second World War.

11
00:07:56,233 --> 00:08:08,695
[SPEAKER_06]: Despite these pressures, the United Nations remains the only universal forum where all member states can come together, an institution that is often a lifeline for millions of people around the world.

12
00:08:09,658 --> 00:08:19,244
[SPEAKER_06]: At the same time, it's being called upon to become more agile, representative and effective, capable of responding to the challenges of the 21st century.

13
00:08:19,884 --> 00:08:31,712
[SPEAKER_06]: And that is why the choice of the next Secretary General is not merely a moment of institutional transition, it is a decision about the very future of multilateralism.

14
00:08:33,352 --> 00:08:37,715
[SPEAKER_06]: The leadership required today demands more than just diplomatic experience.

15
00:08:37,775 --> 00:08:44,019
[SPEAKER_06]: It calls for a figure who can uphold the UN Charter and the principles of international law.

16
00:08:44,479 --> 00:08:48,502
[SPEAKER_06]: Someone who can strengthen cooperation in a fragmented world.

17
00:08:48,902 --> 00:08:53,865
[SPEAKER_06]: Someone who can turn conflict and confrontation into dialogue and negotiation.

18
00:08:54,886 --> 00:09:06,504
[SPEAKER_06]: In a nutshell, the UN Charter's founding principles uphold the human rights of all peoples and equality between men and women and nations, big or small.

19
00:09:08,097 --> 00:09:25,220
[SPEAKER_06]: The UN needs leadership that can act in profoundly difficult, dangerous and complex environments with an understanding of crises on the ground and a genuine commitment to advancing sustainable solutions on a planet increasingly affected by climate change.

20
00:09:26,399 --> 00:09:43,776
[SPEAKER_06]: The legitimacy of the next Secretary General will depend not only on the support of member states, but also on the trust of societies, communities affected by conflict, and younger generations who may question the credibility of the current international system.

21
00:09:45,217 --> 00:09:49,461
[SPEAKER_06]: Today, the candidates come together in a shared public debate space.

22
00:09:50,415 --> 00:09:57,501
[SPEAKER_06]: a place to contrast visions, priorities and leadership approaches in a response to current global challenges.

23
00:09:58,542 --> 00:10:13,135
[SPEAKER_06]: This debate is not only a presentation of candidacies, it is a global conversation at a pivotal time in history about the kind of leadership the international community needs for the years and decades ahead.

24
00:10:26,625 --> 00:10:33,792
[SPEAKER_06]: So a brief outline there of the kind of challenges that lie ahead for the next Secretary General of the United Nations.

25
00:10:33,853 --> 00:10:42,141
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, this is a post which one former Secretary General of the UN described as the most impossible job on this earth.

26
00:10:42,601 --> 00:10:47,006
[SPEAKER_06]: So why on earth do these candidates want to assume the position?

27
00:10:47,587 --> 00:10:49,327
[SPEAKER_06]: me tell you who they are and we'll find out why.

28
00:10:49,628 --> 00:11:13,013
[SPEAKER_06]: Rebecca Grinspan was a vice president in her native Costa Rica and she's currently head of UNCTAD which is the UN's body on trade and development but Rebecca I know you've stepped down temporarily while you're doing all your candidacy stuff so thank you very nice to see you Rebecca and also we have Maria Espinoza from Ecuador where she served as foreign and defense minister and Maria you've also been

29
00:11:13,773 --> 00:11:16,294
[SPEAKER_06]: president of the UN General Assembly, so welcome to you.

30
00:11:16,814 --> 00:11:22,057
[SPEAKER_06]: And Michelle Bachelet was president of Chile until 2018, but she's an old UN hand.

31
00:11:22,077 --> 00:11:26,699
[SPEAKER_06]: She's also been head of UN Women and the UN Human Rights Council.

32
00:11:26,759 --> 00:11:28,720
[SPEAKER_06]: So that is our panel here with us.

33
00:11:29,060 --> 00:11:30,200
[SPEAKER_06]: Welcome to you all.

34
00:11:30,220 --> 00:11:31,281
[SPEAKER_06]: Give them a round of applause.

35
00:11:31,641 --> 00:11:32,081
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

36
00:11:38,969 --> 00:11:41,011
[SPEAKER_06]: As I said at the outset, there are five candidates.

37
00:11:41,051 --> 00:11:46,758
[SPEAKER_06]: We also have President Macisal, former president of Senegal, who was sent us a video intervention.

38
00:11:46,778 --> 00:11:48,960
[SPEAKER_06]: We'll be hearing from him a little bit later.

39
00:11:49,100 --> 00:11:54,286
[SPEAKER_06]: And also Rafael Grossi from Argentina, who was the current head of the IAEA.

40
00:11:54,326 --> 00:11:55,047
[SPEAKER_06]: That's the UN's

41
00:11:55,387 --> 00:11:58,410
[SPEAKER_06]: Body International Atomic Energy Agency.

42
00:11:58,810 --> 00:12:02,474
[SPEAKER_06]: Now he's not available to be with us and he also chose not to send us a video.

43
00:12:02,994 --> 00:12:15,066
[SPEAKER_06]: So now let's start with our questions from our audience here in the Maison de la Paix and the first question is from Eugenia Rogers who's a Geneva Graduate Institute student.

44
00:12:15,526 --> 00:12:17,108
[SPEAKER_06]: Eugenia your question please.

45
00:12:19,175 --> 00:12:20,275
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you very much.

46
00:12:20,455 --> 00:12:22,096
[SPEAKER_07]: It's such a pleasure to be here.

47
00:12:22,796 --> 00:12:35,539
[SPEAKER_07]: My question for you is that many young people around the world feel that multilateral institutions are struggling to deliver on the challenges that matter most to our futures.

48
00:12:36,039 --> 00:12:48,982
[SPEAKER_07]: So what would you do as Secretary General to rebuild trust in the United Nations among younger generations and demonstrate that multilateralism can still be a force for change?

49
00:12:49,322 --> 00:12:49,782
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

50
00:12:50,763 --> 00:12:55,125
[SPEAKER_06]: So let's take that second bit of the question there, because we're going to talk about the role of the SG presently.

51
00:12:55,205 --> 00:12:58,647
[SPEAKER_06]: So how can you revive trust in multilateralism?

52
00:12:59,087 --> 00:12:59,467
[SPEAKER_06]: Rebecca.

53
00:12:59,847 --> 00:13:05,550
[GRYNSPAN]: Well, I think that first, we need to listen to you, not only invite you.

54
00:13:07,251 --> 00:13:14,175
[GRYNSPAN]: I think that it's true that the young people feel very worried about their future.

55
00:13:15,390 --> 00:13:24,012
[GRYNSPAN]: And I think that there is a lot of skepticism, as you said, with respect to the UN and the multilateral system.

56
00:13:25,152 --> 00:13:33,934
[GRYNSPAN]: I will nonetheless call on you not to allow skepticism to go to fatalism.

57
00:13:34,694 --> 00:13:39,015
[GRYNSPAN]: Skepticism is a question, but fatalism is a surrender.

58
00:13:40,015 --> 00:13:50,956
[GRYNSPAN]: So I call on you not to allow anybody to tell you or to tell us that we have no choices and that we cannot do better.

59
00:13:52,012 --> 00:14:10,262
[GRYNSPAN]: My second point is that you will rebuild trust when you will deliver, as you said, in your problems, when we will address conflicts that are recruiting you and displacing you, when we will care about the planet that we

60
00:14:12,583 --> 00:14:33,472
[GRYNSPAN]: that we live in and you will inherit, when we will face the debt problem that doesn't allow your country to invest in their people, in education and health, when we will give you a seat in defining the technologies and what we will do for the future.

61
00:14:33,933 --> 00:14:36,514
[GRYNSPAN]: So delivering on the challenges.

62
00:14:37,264 --> 00:14:39,048
[GRYNSPAN]: But let me ask all of you here.

63
00:14:40,050 --> 00:14:43,378
[GRYNSPAN]: We want you to trust us, but do you know

64
00:14:44,837 --> 00:14:49,220
[GRYNSPAN]: How, what is the percentage of young people under 30 in the U.S.?

65
00:14:49,540 --> 00:14:52,502
[SPEAKER_06]: You're supposed to be answering the questions, not asking them, for any way.

66
00:14:52,782 --> 00:14:53,382
[GRYNSPAN]: Do you know?

67
00:14:54,003 --> 00:14:55,163
[GRYNSPAN]: Do you have any idea?

68
00:14:55,684 --> 00:14:56,624
[GRYNSPAN]: Do you have any idea?

69
00:14:57,024 --> 00:14:57,705
[GRYNSPAN]: Okay, let's assume.

70
00:14:57,725 --> 00:14:58,405
[GRYNSPAN]: Four percent.

71
00:14:58,746 --> 00:14:59,126
[GRYNSPAN]: Oh, right.

72
00:14:59,286 --> 00:14:59,926
[GRYNSPAN]: Four percent.

73
00:15:00,647 --> 00:15:07,191
[GRYNSPAN]: So, an institution that wants you to trust us cannot make you invisible.

74
00:15:08,051 --> 00:15:11,313
[GRYNSPAN]: If you're invisible, you will never trust us.

75
00:15:11,453 --> 00:15:19,076
[GRYNSPAN]: And so, build and trust start also, but what we have to do inside the UN, not only outside the UN.

76
00:15:19,276 --> 00:15:19,696
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

77
00:15:19,776 --> 00:15:21,917
[SPEAKER_06]: Maria Spinoza, your answer to that question.

78
00:15:21,957 --> 00:15:27,360
[SPEAKER_06]: So global challenges require a multilateral response, essentially is what Rebecca's been saying.

79
00:15:28,140 --> 00:15:30,461
[ESPINOSA]: Well, I can relate very well to her.

80
00:15:31,382 --> 00:15:32,222
[ESPINOSA]: I understand

81
00:15:32,900 --> 00:15:36,702
[ESPINOSA]: exactly why one would feel disappointed.

82
00:15:37,402 --> 00:15:40,944
[ESPINOSA]: Because trust is not something you declare, it's something you earn.

83
00:15:41,584 --> 00:15:48,088
[ESPINOSA]: And the way to earn the trust and the credibility is through delivery.

84
00:15:49,126 --> 00:15:57,790
[ESPINOSA]: And I think the UN does not suffer from a crisis of purpose or principles enshrined in the Charter.

85
00:15:58,250 --> 00:16:05,734
[ESPINOSA]: It suffers from a crisis of delivery, of impact, of accountability, and of inclusion.

86
00:16:06,474 --> 00:16:12,697
[ESPINOSA]: And of course, when we see a young person asking that question, we have come up with

87
00:16:13,805 --> 00:16:17,207
[ESPINOSA]: the Declaration on Future Generations, a new office for young people.

88
00:16:17,667 --> 00:16:21,149
[ESPINOSA]: But it is not only about listening to young people.

89
00:16:21,669 --> 00:16:25,891
[ESPINOSA]: It's about having them being the architects of their own future.

90
00:16:26,411 --> 00:16:29,713
[ESPINOSA]: Not the victims, but the agents of transformation.

91
00:16:30,253 --> 00:16:34,855
[ESPINOSA]: In the multilateral space, what that means is decisions that are taking

92
00:16:35,355 --> 00:16:44,902
[ESPINOSA]: in the multilateral space have to listen to the younger generations, have them bring their ideas and innovation, and transform the system.

93
00:16:45,402 --> 00:16:58,912
[ESPINOSA]: As Secretary General, this is the transformation I want to lead, an intergenerational transformation to regain the trust, the credibility, and the purpose of the UN through delivery.

94
00:16:59,472 --> 00:17:01,153
[ESPINOSA]: It is about impact.

95
00:17:01,313 --> 00:17:04,315
[ESPINOSA]: It is about touching and transforming people's lives.

96
00:17:04,675 --> 00:17:08,538
[ESPINOSA]: That's exactly what the UN was called to do.

97
00:17:08,998 --> 00:17:11,700
[ESPINOSA]: The first phrase of the Charter, which is my favorite one,

98
00:17:12,985 --> 00:17:14,386
[ESPINOSA]: is we the peoples.

99
00:17:14,786 --> 00:17:18,968
[ESPINOSA]: And of course, we the peoples is the 1.5 billion young people around there.

100
00:17:19,368 --> 00:17:23,890
[ESPINOSA]: In my own team now as a candidate, most of my team are under 30.

101
00:17:24,411 --> 00:17:25,791
[ESPINOSA]: And it's not to check the box.

102
00:17:26,132 --> 00:17:39,598
[ESPINOSA]: It is about having them giving the intelligence, the advice, and being part of the proposals that I am bringing to the UN, a UN that has to be credible and trusted, has to be earned.

103
00:17:39,778 --> 00:17:40,198
[BACHELET]: Thank you.

104
00:17:40,539 --> 00:17:41,319
[BACHELET]: Michelle Bachelet.

105
00:17:41,599 --> 00:17:44,721
[BACHELET]: Well, I agree with what both have said already, of course.

106
00:17:45,621 --> 00:17:56,387
[BACHELET]: But I think, and I remember once working at UN AIDS, UN Women, and a girl says to me, it's not enough that I'll be sitting in the table.

107
00:17:56,647 --> 00:17:58,428
[BACHELET]: I want to discuss the shape of the table.

108
00:17:59,389 --> 00:18:01,350
[BACHELET]: So young people have ideas.

109
00:18:01,870 --> 00:18:05,052
[BACHELET]: In many of the areas that we see as huge challenges for

110
00:18:05,892 --> 00:18:20,226
[BACHELET]: and need a multilateral answer, like climate change and others, and AI, et cetera, young people can play a direct role because they are creative, they have an innovative perspective, et cetera.

111
00:18:20,706 --> 00:18:26,471
[BACHELET]: So I do believe that what the Secretary General has to do, a future Secretary General, is to ensure

112
00:18:27,212 --> 00:18:32,054
[BACHELET]: that the UN not only communicates better, but really is results oriented.

113
00:18:32,074 --> 00:18:34,934
[BACHELET]: Because, as you said, Maria Fernanda and I agree on that.

114
00:18:35,055 --> 00:18:37,855
[BACHELET]: It's delivering what people will realize.

115
00:18:38,336 --> 00:18:40,796
[BACHELET]: Is this institution doing what they have to do?

116
00:18:40,936 --> 00:18:42,997
[BACHELET]: Is it having the answer that we need?

117
00:18:43,477 --> 00:18:51,840
[BACHELET]: And is it not only listening to us, but because you can listen and not do anything about it afterwards, it's either taking into consideration our demands, our needs.

118
00:18:52,160 --> 00:18:54,741
[BACHELET]: But I have to say also that multilateralism

119
00:18:55,461 --> 00:18:56,422
[BACHELET]: has a lot of problems.

120
00:18:56,482 --> 00:19:02,408
[BACHELET]: But if we didn't have a multilateral system, children in the refugee camps wouldn't have vaccines.

121
00:19:03,009 --> 00:19:07,814
[BACHELET]: People on displacement wouldn't have support.

122
00:19:08,094 --> 00:19:14,040
[BACHELET]: So there's a lot of things that multilateralism has done, and we need to improve everything that needs to be done better.

123
00:19:14,180 --> 00:19:16,922
[SPEAKER_06]: But multilateralism and the UN are not the same thing.

124
00:19:16,942 --> 00:19:21,567
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, there are lots of regional bodies, the African Union, the European Union, ASEAN, and so on.

125
00:19:21,867 --> 00:19:27,892
[SPEAKER_06]: And a lot of people are saying, actually, this is a more pragmatic approach to multilateralism, you know, bite-sized chunk.

126
00:19:27,912 --> 00:19:32,176
[SPEAKER_06]: We're asking too much of the UN, 193 countries, to try and get consensus.

127
00:19:32,616 --> 00:19:35,439
[SPEAKER_06]: It becomes, you know, you just get institutional inertia.

128
00:19:35,846 --> 00:19:39,931
[SPEAKER_06]: So perhaps all of you would just address this issue of regional bodies very quickly.

129
00:19:39,951 --> 00:19:46,039
[SPEAKER_06]: Do you think that perhaps they are less unwieldy than the UN as a multilateral tool?

130
00:19:46,500 --> 00:19:52,147
[BACHELET]: Yes, and I think this is clear, for example, when you have to deal with issues of peace and security.

131
00:19:52,848 --> 00:19:55,810
[BACHELET]: or when we are talking about financing for development.

132
00:19:56,110 --> 00:20:06,056
[BACHELET]: I mean, all these regional groups, and you mentioned many of them, but also the development banks in different regions, can play an important role as well.

133
00:20:07,037 --> 00:20:07,717
[ESPINOSA]: Regional bodies?

134
00:20:08,257 --> 00:20:08,938
[ESPINOSA]: Shout out to them.

135
00:20:10,326 --> 00:20:15,711
[ESPINOSA]: Well, what I would say that the world has changed in these eight years.

136
00:20:16,592 --> 00:20:23,119
[ESPINOSA]: The role of regions, the role of banks, the role of the private sector, it's extremely important.

137
00:20:23,159 --> 00:20:25,841
[ESPINOSA]: The UN is not the only game in town anymore.

138
00:20:26,482 --> 00:20:37,810
[ESPINOSA]: But the UN is irreplaceable because it's the only universal platform that brings all countries together to face and respond to the challenges of the world of today.

139
00:20:38,190 --> 00:20:42,252
[ESPINOSA]: We are living an era of radical interdependence.

140
00:20:42,573 --> 00:20:45,455
[ESPINOSA]: The big question is how we govern interdependence.

141
00:20:45,755 --> 00:20:52,879
[ESPINOSA]: The UN, I think, is absolutely the only universal body that brings everybody together.

142
00:20:52,919 --> 00:20:55,041
[SPEAKER_06]: That's both its strength and weakness you can't get.

143
00:20:55,796 --> 00:21:00,000
[GRYNSPAN]: The phrase I have been using is the UN is unique, but it's not alone.

144
00:21:00,821 --> 00:21:07,506
[GRYNSPAN]: There are much more capacities today outside the UN, not like in 1945.

145
00:21:08,087 --> 00:21:13,131
[GRYNSPAN]: But the UN has a culture problem, because we want everything to come on the UN.

146
00:21:13,551 --> 00:21:17,555
[GRYNSPAN]: We don't know how to deeply partner, real partnership.

147
00:21:19,798 --> 00:21:29,392
[GRYNSPAN]: For example, the African Union, we have resolutions trying to make them a stronger actor in peace and security.

148
00:21:29,812 --> 00:21:32,977
[GRYNSPAN]: We still haven't made that decision.

149
00:21:33,057 --> 00:21:33,978
[GRYNSPAN]: happen.

150
00:21:34,118 --> 00:21:40,545
[GRYNSPAN]: Implementation of real partnerships is really lagging behind because of the culture of the UN.

151
00:21:40,845 --> 00:21:42,067
[GRYNSPAN]: So we need to refocus.

152
00:21:42,527 --> 00:21:43,448
[GRYNSPAN]: We are unique.

153
00:21:43,829 --> 00:21:48,954
[GRYNSPAN]: We have to do the things in which we are unique, but we have to learn how to partner.

154
00:21:49,074 --> 00:21:54,838
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't pose it as a question, but we know that 42% of the UN's funding comes from the United States and China.

155
00:21:54,958 --> 00:22:00,882
[SPEAKER_06]: U.S. currently $4 billion in arrears, and China owes about half a billion currently.

156
00:22:00,982 --> 00:22:04,785
[SPEAKER_06]: So, you know, there is a question of, can you do anything if you don't have the money?

157
00:22:04,845 --> 00:22:10,189
[SPEAKER_06]: And Antonio Guterres, we know, has been saying, I don't have the money, I'm going to run out very soon.

158
00:22:10,249 --> 00:22:12,070
[SPEAKER_06]: But anyway, that's a question for another day.

159
00:22:12,671 --> 00:22:15,052
[BACHELET]: You mentioned the African Union, and indeed...

160
00:22:16,143 --> 00:22:17,444
[SPEAKER_06]: For our nightmares, you mean.

161
00:22:19,224 --> 00:22:24,646
[SPEAKER_06]: That's going to be something for you to grapple with, getting the money if any one of you assumes the role.

162
00:22:24,686 --> 00:22:32,149
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, somebody else who wants to assume the position of Secretary General of the UN is one of our candidates, Maki Sal, former president of Senegal.

163
00:22:32,189 --> 00:22:39,172
[SPEAKER_06]: He couldn't be with us, but he has sent us this video message setting out his perspective on multilateralism.

164
00:22:41,813 --> 00:22:45,955
[SALL]: I believe that the international system is fragmented.

165
00:22:47,148 --> 00:22:49,388
[SALL]: because trust has been weakened.

166
00:22:50,429 --> 00:22:54,850
[SALL]: And without trust, multilateralism cannot deliver.

167
00:22:55,850 --> 00:23:01,891
[SALL]: If selected Secretary General, I would champion three concrete changes.

168
00:23:03,051 --> 00:23:09,953
[SALL]: First, I would work to bring the United Nations back to its member states.

169
00:23:11,173 --> 00:23:16,234
[SALL]: Reform must be owned by countries large

170
00:23:16,838 --> 00:23:19,318
[SALL]: and small, north and south.

171
00:23:20,319 --> 00:23:26,040
[SALL]: The UN must listen more and act with more inclusiveness.

172
00:23:27,920 --> 00:23:46,603
[SALL]: As Secretary General, I will be a bridge builder, someone able to speak to everyone, listen to everyone, bring positions closer, and maintain dialogue even in times of high tension.

173
00:23:48,586 --> 00:23:52,327
[SALL]: Second, I would make the UN more effective on the ground.

174
00:23:53,587 --> 00:24:04,129
[SALL]: When they must be rationalized and clear, resources better used and results better measured.

175
00:24:05,529 --> 00:24:15,731
[SALL]: Third, while taking care of human rights, I would also make development a central pillar of peace.

176
00:24:16,852 --> 00:24:18,312
[SALL]: We cannot fight terrorism.

177
00:24:19,005 --> 00:24:24,608
[SALL]: instability or migration only with security responses.

178
00:24:26,289 --> 00:24:41,456
[SALL]: We must win the battle of development by promoting jobs for youth, women, investment, infrastructure, climate justice, and fair access to finance.

179
00:24:43,017 --> 00:24:46,759
[SALL]: The Secretary General has no army and no police

180
00:24:48,027 --> 00:24:56,090
[SALL]: His true strength is credibility, impartiality, and moral authority.

181
00:24:57,391 --> 00:24:59,592
[SALL]: I'm not running for a career.

182
00:25:00,692 --> 00:25:15,258
[SALL]: I'm running for impact to rebuild trust, restore dialogue, and help make the United Nations a stronger tool of collective action.

183
00:25:18,948 --> 00:25:27,438
[SPEAKER_06]: Mackie Sell, the former president of Senegal, making his pitch on how he would restore trust in the UN and deliver on multilateralism.

184
00:25:27,999 --> 00:25:37,009
[SPEAKER_06]: So now we can go to a second question from our audience and former executive director of the Kofi Annan Foundation, Kofi Annan of course,

185
00:25:37,970 --> 00:25:40,891
[SPEAKER_06]: the late Kofi Annan, a former Secretary General of the UN himself.

186
00:25:40,972 --> 00:25:46,454
[SPEAKER_06]: And we have a question from Corinne Momal Vanillon on leadership.

187
00:25:46,654 --> 00:25:47,014
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

188
00:25:47,735 --> 00:25:48,475
[SPEAKER_08]: Good afternoon.

189
00:25:48,975 --> 00:25:56,699
[SPEAKER_08]: And the question I'd like to ask the candidates is, what is their vision of the role of the Secretary General in peace and security?

190
00:25:56,899 --> 00:25:59,040
[SPEAKER_08]: Is it that of a Secretary General

191
00:25:59,540 --> 00:26:11,969
[SPEAKER_08]: who is a political actor in her own right and who can take initiatives and shape global diplomacy along the lines of articulated by Boutros Boutros-Ghali 30 years ago in his Agenda for Peace?

192
00:26:12,650 --> 00:26:25,379
[SPEAKER_08]: Or is it more of a Secretary General focused primarily on facilitating cooperation among member states as put forward by Antonio Guterres in his new Agenda for Peace three years ago?

193
00:26:25,719 --> 00:26:26,400
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you very much.

194
00:26:27,475 --> 00:26:42,441
[SPEAKER_06]: OK, I should just add that there is something in the charter, isn't there, the UN Charter Article 99, which allows the Secretary General to invoke, to take it to the Security Council if he, she feels that there's a real threat to international peace and security.

195
00:26:42,461 --> 00:26:49,404
[SPEAKER_06]: And Antony Guterres, I believe, has only actually ever done this once in 2023 during the Israel-Gaza conflict and so on.

196
00:26:49,824 --> 00:26:55,587
[SPEAKER_06]: So just to bear that in mind as well, whether you would trigger the use of Article 99.

197
00:26:55,647 --> 00:26:55,947
[SPEAKER_06]: Maria.

198
00:26:57,664 --> 00:26:59,765
[ESPINOSA]: Well, I didn't say that, but...

199
00:27:00,165 --> 00:27:04,547
[ESPINOSA]: In English, if we... Yeah, in English, but I think...

200
00:27:13,792 --> 00:27:16,833
[ESPINOSA]: Multilingualism is extremely important.

201
00:27:17,694 --> 00:27:21,095
[ESPINOSA]: I think the French language is also very important.

202
00:27:21,655 --> 00:27:30,978
[ESPINOSA]: In the hub of the UN here in Geneva, it's a francophone, and I understand that there is no translation, but I wanted to say hello.

203
00:27:31,319 --> 00:27:33,179
[ESPINOSA]: You all speak French, don't you?

204
00:27:33,379 --> 00:27:34,460
[ESPINOSA]: And bonjour, and bonjour.

205
00:27:35,340 --> 00:27:39,743
[ESPINOSA]: And my question is not an either-or response.

206
00:27:40,223 --> 00:27:51,710
[ESPINOSA]: I think a secretary-general should use every tool provided in the charter to be, first of all, work very strongly on prevention.

207
00:27:51,750 --> 00:27:55,653
[ESPINOSA]: That's why I'm proposing a prevention and early action hub.

208
00:27:56,673 --> 00:28:10,139
[ESPINOSA]: has to work as a peacemaker, has to work also to support others when they take the lead on peacemaking, and has to be an onus broker and impartial agent.

209
00:28:10,420 --> 00:28:15,822
[ESPINOSA]: But impartiality doesn't mean a silence or paralysis.

210
00:28:16,302 --> 00:28:20,823
[ESPINOSA]: It really means to be able to bring all the parties together.

211
00:28:21,343 --> 00:28:24,864
[ESPINOSA]: I did that when I was president of the UN General Assembly.

212
00:28:25,244 --> 00:28:32,225
[ESPINOSA]: I brought 193 countries together to discuss very complex and contentious issues.

213
00:28:32,725 --> 00:28:44,767
[ESPINOSA]: It's the ability to convene, the ability to really serve as a true bridge builder, but it is also to be active, to be present, to be present, to be seen

214
00:28:45,287 --> 00:28:50,851
[ESPINOSA]: when a conflict is about to erupt or when a conflict has already happened.

215
00:28:51,411 --> 00:28:55,595
[ESPINOSA]: Early warning, early action are of utmost importance.

216
00:28:56,115 --> 00:29:07,703
[ESPINOSA]: As we said, the UN is not the only game in town, but the secretary-general should be foot on the ground, active, present, engaged, and be trusted by all member states.

217
00:29:07,843 --> 00:29:10,806
[SPEAKER_06]: So a UN secretary-general out in the field as much as possible.

218
00:29:10,906 --> 00:29:11,966
[SPEAKER_06]: OK, Michelle Bachelet.

219
00:29:12,907 --> 00:29:15,390
[BACHELET]: I agree also that you have to be both.

220
00:29:16,311 --> 00:29:20,795
[BACHELET]: And of course it will depend on the moment and which is the role that you have to play.

221
00:29:21,736 --> 00:29:34,549
[BACHELET]: On one hand, if you have a person who wants to facilitate, but that has no independent judgement, that's not going to be a facilitator, that's going to be a moderator, and the UN doesn't need a moderator as Secretary General.

222
00:29:35,410 --> 00:29:47,956
[BACHELET]: If you have, on the other hand, somebody who is independent but has no capability to build trust across the different sides of the problem, you will not be a peacemaker, you will be a commentator of news.

223
00:29:48,396 --> 00:29:53,639
[BACHELET]: So we need somebody who understands the moment, and we have the tools.

224
00:29:53,799 --> 00:29:55,900
[BACHELET]: It's not true that we don't have the tools.

225
00:29:56,380 --> 00:29:58,441
[BACHELET]: The Shutter mentions many of them.

226
00:29:58,941 --> 00:30:01,302
[BACHELET]: Of course, the good offices.

227
00:30:01,762 --> 00:30:03,122
[BACHELET]: Of course, early warning.

228
00:30:03,303 --> 00:30:04,963
[BACHELET]: You need to have early warning signs.

229
00:30:05,483 --> 00:30:06,584
[BACHELET]: You need to mediate.

230
00:30:06,604 --> 00:30:11,165
[BACHELET]: You need to identify who can be your allies in terms of making good results.

231
00:30:11,525 --> 00:30:15,587
[BACHELET]: There's a lot of things that many of us in our former capacity have done many times.

232
00:30:16,527 --> 00:30:18,608
[BACHELET]: The thing I think is not the lack of tools.

233
00:30:18,648 --> 00:30:23,851
[BACHELET]: The problem we have is there's no capacity in the system to read the early warning signs.

234
00:30:23,911 --> 00:30:29,414
[BACHELET]: And I've said it many times, and I've discussed this, being executive director, UN Women, and as high commissioner.

235
00:30:30,655 --> 00:30:35,457
[BACHELET]: I always said that I don't have the time now, that I went to a country, I knew there was going to come coup d'etat.

236
00:30:35,598 --> 00:30:40,060
[BACHELET]: I mentioned to everybody, everybody said I was crazy, and the coup d'etat came two weeks later.

237
00:30:40,480 --> 00:30:43,422
[BACHELET]: Because you have to read what's happening in the country.

238
00:30:44,262 --> 00:30:52,230
[BACHELET]: The last thing I have to say is that by many times what the Secretary needs to do is to facilitate the relation between countries.

239
00:30:52,510 --> 00:30:56,914
[BACHELET]: For example, to find a room or space where people can come together and dialogue.

240
00:30:57,415 --> 00:31:02,940
[BACHELET]: But on the other hand, or to open channels when people are refusing to speak to each other.

241
00:31:03,570 --> 00:31:06,112
[BACHELET]: Sometimes silence cannot happen.

242
00:31:06,533 --> 00:31:08,154
[BACHELET]: You cannot be a complex of silence.

243
00:31:08,234 --> 00:31:11,617
[BACHELET]: If civilians are being killed, the Secretary General has to speak.

244
00:31:12,237 --> 00:31:14,880
[BACHELET]: But also has to work and dialogue with all members of state.

245
00:31:14,900 --> 00:31:17,462
[BACHELET]: That doesn't mean dialogue, doesn't mean endorsement.

246
00:31:17,902 --> 00:31:22,586
[BACHELET]: I mean, you can dialogue and work with countries that you have, or governments that you have criticized.

247
00:31:22,646 --> 00:31:24,868
[BACHELET]: I have worked with governments I have publicly criticized.

248
00:31:25,428 --> 00:31:26,709
[BACHELET]: But that doesn't mean endorsement.

249
00:31:26,729 --> 00:31:30,673
[BACHELET]: It means that you have to engage to try to produce the results needed.

250
00:31:31,213 --> 00:31:45,563
[BACHELET]: So I think the second area has to be both, and the thing is to identify what can work, because sometimes preventive diplomacy is very important, sometimes you have to be actively on the field mediating, but anticipating.

251
00:31:45,603 --> 00:31:51,447
[BACHELET]: I think the US has difficulties to anticipate and to prevent crisis from happening.

252
00:31:52,247 --> 00:31:52,607
[BACHELET]: Rebecca.

253
00:31:53,408 --> 00:31:58,872
[GRYNSPAN]: Well, hearing the question, the first thing that comes to mind is Kofi Annan.

254
00:31:59,712 --> 00:32:04,716
[GRYNSPAN]: Yes, Kofi Annan was an independent leader and a very effective leader at the same time.

255
00:32:05,396 --> 00:32:10,680
[GRYNSPAN]: So his example is a good one to follow.

256
00:32:11,220 --> 00:32:19,807
[GRYNSPAN]: I think that my criteria of success as SGE is that nobody will ask me again

257
00:32:20,687 --> 00:32:22,348
[GRYNSPAN]: Where is the UN?

258
00:32:24,249 --> 00:32:28,031
[GRYNSPAN]: If that question continues, we will be irrelevant.

259
00:32:28,652 --> 00:32:31,053
[GRYNSPAN]: So the important thing is to be there.

260
00:32:31,654 --> 00:32:35,016
[GRYNSPAN]: We have become too risk-averse.

261
00:32:36,082 --> 00:32:37,363
[GRYNSPAN]: We cannot do that.

262
00:32:38,104 --> 00:32:42,066
[GRYNSPAN]: Our only risk and our only failure is not to try.

263
00:32:42,667 --> 00:32:46,029
[GRYNSPAN]: And in many cases, I have to say, we have stopped trying.

264
00:32:46,830 --> 00:32:58,939
[GRYNSPAN]: And we have to try and try again because we are the ones, and the Secretary General is the person, that can assume the cost of failure, the cost of rejection.

265
00:32:59,739 --> 00:33:00,600
[GRYNSPAN]: And we have to do that.

266
00:33:00,820 --> 00:33:03,522
[GRYNSPAN]: We have to be courageous to be able to do that.

267
00:33:04,002 --> 00:33:06,184
[GRYNSPAN]: Try again and try again.

268
00:33:06,304 --> 00:33:10,287
[GRYNSPAN]: We have to navigate many no's until we get a yes.

269
00:33:10,667 --> 00:33:15,030
[GRYNSPAN]: That's what happened when I intervened in the Black Sea Initiative.

270
00:33:15,230 --> 00:33:17,692
[GRYNSPAN]: Yes, nobody believed that we could do that.

271
00:33:18,052 --> 00:33:28,500
[GRYNSPAN]: We did that within the framework of a war, but we understood that we can agree on something that can be important for millions of people in the world

272
00:33:29,020 --> 00:33:31,282
[GRYNSPAN]: even if we don't agree on everything.

273
00:33:32,223 --> 00:33:34,065
[GRYNSPAN]: And the other thing is to engage.

274
00:33:34,766 --> 00:33:35,547
[GRYNSPAN]: We have said that.

275
00:33:36,007 --> 00:33:42,774
[GRYNSPAN]: I believe in early warning, but to tell you the truth, early warning is not an information system.

276
00:33:43,394 --> 00:33:48,640
[GRYNSPAN]: We many times think about early warning as a lot of information that we see indicators.

277
00:33:49,100 --> 00:33:56,306
[GRYNSPAN]: No, early warning is to listen to the ground, is to listen to the people that is in all the countries of the world.

278
00:33:56,726 --> 00:34:04,092
[GRYNSPAN]: And sometimes the headquarters is a wall between the ground and what

279
00:34:04,432 --> 00:34:06,653
[GRYNSPAN]: the decisions that have to be taken.

280
00:34:06,913 --> 00:34:12,976
[GRYNSPAN]: And just the last point, for that to be effective, you have to have the best team.

281
00:34:13,477 --> 00:34:20,860
[GRYNSPAN]: We have to change the office of the Secretary General and have the best team with the Secretary General to be effective.

282
00:34:20,881 --> 00:34:22,381
[SPEAKER_06]: You mentioned the Black Sea thing.

283
00:34:22,401 --> 00:34:29,225
[SPEAKER_06]: That's the Ukraine, UN-Turkey agreement that was struck to allow Ukraine to export its grain.

284
00:34:30,385 --> 00:34:52,857
[SPEAKER_06]: during throughout this the conflict because obviously lots of countries were not getting their grain from Ukraine which has seen as a great success I think 2022-23 but you know a lot of people would say we you know gone are the days when we saw a UN Secretary General shuffling between Washington and Moscow trying to sort out the Cuba missile crisis Javier Perez de Cuellar

285
00:34:53,317 --> 00:35:01,130
[SPEAKER_06]: in 1988, mediating between Iraq and Iran, Dag Hammarskjöld famously trying to bring peace through the Congo and so on.

286
00:35:01,271 --> 00:35:03,094
[SPEAKER_06]: As the world's top diplomat,

287
00:35:04,435 --> 00:35:07,297
[SPEAKER_06]: A lot of people are now saying, you're absent, you're irrelevant.

288
00:35:07,357 --> 00:35:14,780
[SPEAKER_06]: Antonio Guterres says the US-Israeli war on Iran is illegal, but nobody really pays any attention.

289
00:35:14,841 --> 00:35:18,282
[SPEAKER_06]: So all of you are obviously women.

290
00:35:18,663 --> 00:35:22,945
[SPEAKER_06]: We've not to date had a secretary general who is female.

291
00:35:22,985 --> 00:35:25,506
[SPEAKER_06]: You go to the UN headquarters and all the pictures, of course, are men.

292
00:35:25,546 --> 00:35:26,747
[SPEAKER_06]: This is the 10th one.

293
00:35:27,127 --> 00:35:28,948
[SPEAKER_06]: I just wonder if all of you could just answer

294
00:35:29,328 --> 00:35:36,051
[SPEAKER_06]: this point, do you feel that, particularly in terms of your diplomatic skills, that your gender brings something different to the table, Michelle?

295
00:35:37,191 --> 00:35:44,455
[BACHELET]: Well, I think that gender, yes, but not any women, if I have to say.

296
00:35:45,195 --> 00:35:52,878
[BACHELET]: One of the reasons that I've been in many different posts is because I'm not trying to maintain myself at that post, I try to do what needs to be done.

297
00:35:53,879 --> 00:35:56,000
[BACHELET]: So I'm not afraid of

298
00:35:57,140 --> 00:35:59,601
[BACHELET]: risking that what I try doesn't work.

299
00:36:00,362 --> 00:36:02,623
[BACHELET]: I'm not afraid of speaking up when it's needed.

300
00:36:03,063 --> 00:36:10,548
[BACHELET]: I'm not afraid to take a plane and get into the place where I need to be, where I have to talk to and produce a dialogue.

301
00:36:10,568 --> 00:36:22,754
[BACHELET]: So I think women that are there to do these kind of things, we're not too many candidates, not many there, it's because we really believe that we want to put our energy and to produce the results needed for the world.

302
00:36:22,974 --> 00:36:23,655
[SPEAKER_06]: Marius, Vanessa.

303
00:36:24,888 --> 00:36:28,115
[ESPINOSA]: Well, I think, of course, a woman, it's about time, isn't it?

304
00:36:28,436 --> 00:36:30,039
[ESPINOSA]: After 80 years, of course.

305
00:36:33,381 --> 00:36:39,644
[ESPINOSA]: What I say is we need a 360 leader with a lot of energy.

306
00:36:39,964 --> 00:36:40,765
[ESPINOSA]: What does it mean?

307
00:36:41,245 --> 00:36:43,686
[ESPINOSA]: It's that you master the three pillars of the UN.

308
00:36:44,326 --> 00:36:53,270
[ESPINOSA]: That you've been Minister of Defense and it's not that I want to speak about my own bio, but you really need to master.

309
00:36:54,591 --> 00:36:58,213
[ESPINOSA]: You need to master the three pillars, understand how they come together,

310
00:36:58,893 --> 00:37:01,737
[ESPINOSA]: and have the energy to act and transform.

311
00:37:02,538 --> 00:37:05,742
[ESPINOSA]: I differ about the issue of prevention.

312
00:37:06,322 --> 00:37:10,347
[ESPINOSA]: Prevention and early warning have to be more than a slogan.

313
00:37:11,228 --> 00:37:13,772
[ESPINOSA]: It has to be an operating principle.

314
00:37:14,272 --> 00:37:22,034
[ESPINOSA]: It has to be the tool that the secretary general has to inform and to advise member states so they can act.

315
00:37:22,534 --> 00:37:24,755
[ESPINOSA]: To inform yourself so you can act.

316
00:37:25,115 --> 00:37:31,917
[ESPINOSA]: So basically a 360 secretary general and of course a woman, the best woman, not any woman.

317
00:37:31,957 --> 00:37:32,137
[ESPINOSA]: Okay.

318
00:37:32,757 --> 00:37:34,358
[SPEAKER_06]: Rebecca on this issue of gender.

319
00:37:34,798 --> 00:37:38,539
[GRYNSPAN]: I'm running to be secretary general because I think I am the best person for the job.

320
00:37:39,879 --> 00:37:40,820
[GRYNSPAN]: Okay.

321
00:37:40,860 --> 00:37:41,560
[GRYNSPAN]: Short and sweet.

322
00:37:41,600 --> 00:37:42,000
[GRYNSPAN]: Thank you.

323
00:37:46,238 --> 00:37:48,681
[SPEAKER_06]: And there is a sort of unwritten thought.

324
00:37:48,701 --> 00:37:54,366
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, it's not actually stated explicitly that it is the turn of Latin America and the Caribbean.

325
00:37:54,606 --> 00:37:57,429
[SPEAKER_06]: And, of course, we also... We also...

326
00:37:58,169 --> 00:37:58,470
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean...

327
00:38:02,194 --> 00:38:04,155
[SPEAKER_06]: That's just a sort of convention.

328
00:38:04,596 --> 00:38:08,559
[SPEAKER_06]: I think the last person was Javier Pérez de Cuea from Peru, wasn't it?

329
00:38:09,299 --> 00:38:10,380
[SPEAKER_06]: And that was in the 80s.

330
00:38:10,480 --> 00:38:15,804
[SPEAKER_06]: So now let's go to another question from our audience, a graduate of NYU in New York.

331
00:38:15,944 --> 00:38:20,987
[SPEAKER_06]: And Tamao Chika, you want to ask a question on the burning topic of climate.

332
00:38:21,428 --> 00:38:21,768
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

333
00:38:22,080 --> 00:38:22,941
[SPEAKER_00]: Hi, thank you so much.

334
00:38:23,561 --> 00:38:28,685
[SPEAKER_00]: As a young person, I will live with the consequences of climate change and climate decisions made today.

335
00:38:29,406 --> 00:38:36,732
[SPEAKER_00]: Yet many countries most affected by climate change often have the least influence over global climate decisions and face debt burdens.

336
00:38:37,932 --> 00:38:45,378
[SPEAKER_00]: And climate change is an intersectional issue in which forced migration disproportionately affects women in marginalized communities.

337
00:38:46,198 --> 00:38:54,504
[SPEAKER_00]: So as sector general, how would you ensure the climate governance becomes more equitable in response to those on the front lines of the crisis?

338
00:38:54,784 --> 00:38:55,165
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

339
00:38:55,723 --> 00:39:00,726
[SPEAKER_06]: Michel Bachelet, there are so many facets to climate, of course, but that one seems essentially about climate justice.

340
00:39:01,126 --> 00:39:22,617
[BACHELET]: It's really important what she was mentioning, because the places were being more affected, we're talking about small islands, for example, or low coastal communities, or communities who live in places where they are already having the impact of high sea levels, and of course of the extreme weather.

341
00:39:23,157 --> 00:39:27,619
[BACHELET]: They're usually, as you mentioned correctly, they're not sitting at the table where they make decisions.

342
00:39:28,180 --> 00:39:38,125
[BACHELET]: And I think the Secretary General, one of the things it needs to be doing, on one hand, is to ensure that the secretariat and the whole system more representative.

343
00:39:38,565 --> 00:39:47,430
[BACHELET]: Countries who usually don't have those places, they have to be there so they can bring their issues, not only in the General Assembly, but also inside the office of the Secretary General.

344
00:39:47,970 --> 00:39:54,352
[BACHELET]: I think also that we need to ensure that what we sign, I sign as President of the Republic the agreement to Paris.

345
00:39:54,912 --> 00:39:56,153
[BACHELET]: And we know what needs to be done.

346
00:39:56,193 --> 00:39:57,833
[BACHELET]: We all know what works.

347
00:39:58,394 --> 00:40:07,797
[BACHELET]: And what is lacking is, on one hand, enough finance, because the loss and damage fund was a great idea, but it's under-capitalized, so it's not working.

348
00:40:08,297 --> 00:40:10,738
[BACHELET]: And we also need to implement the Paris Agreement.

349
00:40:11,358 --> 00:40:30,224
[BACHELET]: And in that sense, what I would do is I would bring together all the communities that are affected, I mean, sit with them, with the member states, and create sort of a big, big, I would say, sense of urgency that we need to deal with this, because it's not a matter of future, it's a matter of life.

350
00:40:30,924 --> 00:40:33,826
[BACHELET]: taken today, and of course in the future generations.

351
00:40:34,447 --> 00:40:45,696
[BACHELET]: But I also believe that we need to ensure that all the finance given to those member states that are fighting with a terrible debt

352
00:40:46,797 --> 00:40:49,319
[BACHELET]: It's not possible that it has to be given by loans.

353
00:40:49,639 --> 00:40:53,303
[BACHELET]: They have to receive money with grants because they cannot.

354
00:40:53,723 --> 00:41:04,774
[BACHELET]: I mean, they're drowning and we're asking them to ask for loans with a debt service that's so big, it's higher than they can use in health, in education, but also in climate mitigation and adaptation.

355
00:41:05,234 --> 00:41:25,199
[BACHELET]: So we need to change many things to continue pushing for the urgency that is for humanity, climate change, but not only climate change, pollution, and of course a loss of biodiversity, the triple issue, but also to ensure that the countries have the way to respond to that.

356
00:41:25,639 --> 00:41:26,539
[BACHELET]: Rebecca Greenspan?

357
00:41:27,359 --> 00:41:28,159
[GRYNSPAN]: Yes.

358
00:41:29,060 --> 00:41:34,821
[GRYNSPAN]: Well, I worked extensively on the intersection of climate and development.

359
00:41:35,762 --> 00:41:46,112
[GRYNSPAN]: When I was vice president of my country and the minister of finance before that, Costa Rica reverted with the right policies the forestation.

360
00:41:46,892 --> 00:41:52,076
[GRYNSPAN]: We have today a greener country than we did 40 years ago.

361
00:41:53,337 --> 00:41:58,821
[GRYNSPAN]: And we started with the services for environment, environmental services.

362
00:41:59,762 --> 00:42:09,709
[GRYNSPAN]: And we really strengthened the voice of Costa Rica in the international community because we were credible, we walked the talk.

363
00:42:10,590 --> 00:42:18,402
[GRYNSPAN]: So I think that that is very important in terms of helping and supporting countries with the right policies inside the countries.

364
00:42:19,244 --> 00:42:22,108
[GRYNSPAN]: But second, what the UN can do.

365
00:42:22,769 --> 00:42:25,794
[GRYNSPAN]: First, I think that we need to bring adaptation

366
00:42:26,334 --> 00:42:29,477
[GRYNSPAN]: to also the discussion, not only mitigation.

367
00:42:29,937 --> 00:42:37,703
[GRYNSPAN]: Countries, and you mentioned Shell, the seats or the LDCs, are already suffering the consequence of climate change.

368
00:42:38,123 --> 00:42:44,749
[GRYNSPAN]: So, financing adaptation and the adaptation agenda is central to what we are discussing.

369
00:42:45,389 --> 00:42:50,812
[GRYNSPAN]: Second, we have to scale up finance, but we have also to simplify finance.

370
00:42:51,172 --> 00:43:01,438
[GRYNSPAN]: You know, countries spend years sometimes to be able to get a loan from the funds that we have, from the climate funds and the environmental funds that we already have.

371
00:43:01,498 --> 00:43:03,279
[GRYNSPAN]: They don't have the capacities many times.

372
00:43:03,779 --> 00:43:05,760
[GRYNSPAN]: It's cumbersome and it's bureaucratic.

373
00:43:05,800 --> 00:43:08,482
[GRYNSPAN]: We have to change also the system.

374
00:43:08,962 --> 00:43:21,232
[GRYNSPAN]: And third, we have to bring the multilateral development banks and the private sector to the financial flows to go to the countries that are not receiving them.

375
00:43:21,872 --> 00:43:31,240
[GRYNSPAN]: Only 2% of the foreign direct investment in renewable energy goes to Africa, 2% of the total of the world.

376
00:43:31,820 --> 00:43:41,462
[GRYNSPAN]: If we don't partner with the multilateral system, with the multilateral development banks, in crowding private investment, it won't happen in these countries.

377
00:43:41,782 --> 00:43:44,783
[GRYNSPAN]: And lastly, you know, the clauses for debt.

378
00:43:44,903 --> 00:43:47,304
[GRYNSPAN]: I think that Michelle, you mentioned that.

379
00:43:47,364 --> 00:43:48,704
[GRYNSPAN]: I think that that's very important.

380
00:43:49,104 --> 00:44:01,367
[GRYNSPAN]: Debt and climate have to be part of the same conversation, because today the countries don't have the fiscal space to invest in their people and to invest in the transition.

381
00:44:01,828 --> 00:44:03,453
[GRYNSPAN]: for a sustainable development.

382
00:44:03,733 --> 00:44:04,656
[GRYNSPAN]: Maria Spinoza.

383
00:44:05,899 --> 00:44:09,720
[ESPINOSA]: Well, I love that question because I share the same frustration.

384
00:44:10,201 --> 00:44:12,682
[ESPINOSA]: I have been a climate negotiator for decades.

385
00:44:12,982 --> 00:44:26,187
[ESPINOSA]: And believe me, I don't know what was more difficult, climate negotiations or when I led the peace talks between the ELN and the government of Colombia, frankly.

386
00:44:26,587 --> 00:44:31,389
[ESPINOSA]: Why is that we have had 30 cops, very soon 31,

387
00:44:32,809 --> 00:44:49,357
[ESPINOSA]: 31 times we have met to discuss and agree and decide, and emissions continue to grow, and climate shocks continue to destroy lives, livelihoods, your future and the future of younger generations.

388
00:44:49,877 --> 00:44:51,458
[ESPINOSA]: So there is a frustration there.

389
00:44:51,778 --> 00:44:53,619
[ESPINOSA]: But why is it so difficult?

390
00:44:54,219 --> 00:44:58,361
[ESPINOSA]: It is difficult because climate is not an environmental issue only.

391
00:44:59,041 --> 00:45:00,562
[ESPINOSA]: It is a development issue.

392
00:45:01,762 --> 00:45:03,483
[ESPINOSA]: It is a macroeconomic issue.

393
00:45:04,003 --> 00:45:05,404
[ESPINOSA]: It's a security issue.

394
00:45:06,144 --> 00:45:09,205
[ESPINOSA]: It's an industrialization and competitiveness issue.

395
00:45:09,706 --> 00:45:12,147
[ESPINOSA]: So that is why it's so difficult.

396
00:45:12,847 --> 00:45:17,089
[ESPINOSA]: Saying it is difficult, I'm not saying it is impossible.

397
00:45:17,269 --> 00:45:21,530
[ESPINOSA]: I truly believe that climate change is human-made.

398
00:45:21,650 --> 00:45:22,951
[ESPINOSA]: It was created by us.

399
00:45:23,491 --> 00:45:24,772
[ESPINOSA]: And the solutions are there.

400
00:45:25,652 --> 00:45:32,258
[ESPINOSA]: because we have the technologies, we have the knowledge, we need to scale up finance, but there is plenty of money out there.

401
00:45:32,798 --> 00:45:38,623
[ESPINOSA]: What we need is the vision, the political will, the voices and the agency of young people.

402
00:45:39,023 --> 00:45:49,532
[ESPINOSA]: We need indigenous peoples at the table, we need the private sector, and we need to bring, as my colleagues have said so clearly, we need to bring the discussion on debt,

403
00:45:50,192 --> 00:45:56,315
[ESPINOSA]: on fiscal space, on foreign investment, on supply chains to the climate discussion.

404
00:45:56,835 --> 00:45:57,495
[ESPINOSA]: Is it easy?

405
00:45:57,915 --> 00:46:06,579
[ESPINOSA]: It is not easy, but it can be done, especially if the younger generations are part of the solutions and are agents of transformation.

406
00:46:06,739 --> 00:46:08,160
[SPEAKER_06]: You all say it can be done.

407
00:46:08,180 --> 00:46:09,040
[SPEAKER_06]: You've all provided

408
00:46:09,340 --> 00:46:12,382
[SPEAKER_06]: excellent analysis about why we should do it and so on.

409
00:46:12,442 --> 00:46:17,286
[SPEAKER_06]: But it comes against a very difficult global landscape.

410
00:46:17,326 --> 00:46:19,268
[SPEAKER_06]: You know, you mentioned the Paris Treaty.

411
00:46:19,308 --> 00:46:23,511
[SPEAKER_06]: The US, of course, withdrew in completing that in 2020.

412
00:46:24,071 --> 00:46:32,037
[SPEAKER_06]: The problems with the state of Hormuz conflict has renewed, rekindled everybody's interests in the use of fossil fuels and so on.

413
00:46:32,477 --> 00:46:37,441
[SPEAKER_06]: Not necessarily new exploration, but certainly a retreat back into gas.

414
00:46:37,501 --> 00:46:38,242
[SPEAKER_06]: And you mentioned

415
00:46:38,722 --> 00:46:40,883
[SPEAKER_06]: you know, the money and how little has gone in.

416
00:46:40,903 --> 00:46:50,687
[SPEAKER_06]: And we know that 2009, the Copenhagen climate summit said, you know, $100 billion a year should be paid into adaptation and mitigation.

417
00:46:51,347 --> 00:46:53,928
[SPEAKER_06]: But so far, only fractions of money have come in.

418
00:46:54,048 --> 00:46:58,270
[SPEAKER_06]: So all I can say is good luck to the next Secretary General.

419
00:46:59,635 --> 00:47:08,499
[SPEAKER_06]: on, you know, trying to bring about change on this very, very difficult agenda because, you know, the money and the atmosphere has really, really changed.

420
00:47:08,539 --> 00:47:11,880
[SPEAKER_06]: All right, well, you said that climate is related to development.

421
00:47:11,960 --> 00:47:20,864
[SPEAKER_06]: In fact, we do have a question about development from Martin Chung Gong, who's the outgoing Secretary General of the Inter-Parliamentary Union, till the end of this month.

422
00:47:21,445 --> 00:47:22,305
[SPEAKER_06]: Martin's in position.

423
00:47:22,325 --> 00:47:23,105
[SPEAKER_06]: Martin, your question.

424
00:47:23,566 --> 00:47:24,966
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you very much, Zaina.

425
00:47:25,526 --> 00:47:26,647
[SPEAKER_01]: Congratulations to the

426
00:47:27,343 --> 00:47:29,044
[SPEAKER_01]: candidates here.

427
00:47:29,444 --> 00:47:40,752
[SPEAKER_01]: The next Secretary General of the UN will assume office in early 2027, less than three years to the expiry of the Sustainable Development Goals.

428
00:47:41,612 --> 00:47:47,316
[SPEAKER_01]: And we are generally agreed that these goals, when it comes to progress, has been uneven

429
00:47:48,180 --> 00:47:53,101
[SPEAKER_01]: and in some cases insufficient, largely off track.

430
00:47:53,821 --> 00:48:02,443
[SPEAKER_01]: So as the next Secretary General of the UN, how do you propose to work to bring these SDGs back on track?

431
00:48:03,343 --> 00:48:10,385
[SPEAKER_01]: And subsidiary question, do you consider it important to engage national parliaments in this conversation?

432
00:48:10,985 --> 00:48:11,405
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

433
00:48:13,296 --> 00:48:16,017
[SPEAKER_06]: So quite right.

434
00:48:16,037 --> 00:48:22,418
[SPEAKER_06]: They were pledges that people pledged, governments pledged, but there was no real legal undertaking.

435
00:48:22,458 --> 00:48:25,018
[SPEAKER_06]: So you say slightly off-track, I'll just give you an idea.

436
00:48:25,078 --> 00:48:30,599
[SPEAKER_06]: As you all know, 17 sustainable development goals with about 169 targets.

437
00:48:30,719 --> 00:48:35,440
[SPEAKER_06]: Only 18% of those 169 targets have actually been met.

438
00:48:35,860 --> 00:48:38,321
[SPEAKER_06]: And there's a deficit of about $4 trillion a year.

439
00:48:39,701 --> 00:48:42,122
[SPEAKER_06]: globally to try to meet these SDGs.

440
00:48:42,162 --> 00:48:47,564
[SPEAKER_06]: So you can see 2030, a mere four years away, and we are way off track.

441
00:48:48,004 --> 00:48:49,645
[SPEAKER_06]: Rebecca, your answer please.

442
00:48:49,965 --> 00:48:50,345
[GRYNSPAN]: Thank you.

443
00:48:50,885 --> 00:48:51,885
[GRYNSPAN]: Very easy one.

444
00:48:53,786 --> 00:49:01,649
[GRYNSPAN]: Let me first say that I am really worried about some of the indicators going backward, not even forward.

445
00:49:03,109 --> 00:49:06,651
[GRYNSPAN]: We have 96 million people today

446
00:49:07,531 --> 00:49:10,754
[GRYNSPAN]: in hunger more than in 2015.

447
00:49:11,574 --> 00:49:19,600
[GRYNSPAN]: So we are talking here about really serious backlash that started also with COVID.

448
00:49:19,981 --> 00:49:24,704
[GRYNSPAN]: We forgot COVID already, but many of the countries will never recover.

449
00:49:25,165 --> 00:49:30,289
[GRYNSPAN]: And also hunger that has come with conflict has gone up.

450
00:49:30,969 --> 00:49:45,198
[GRYNSPAN]: And so I think that it's very important that, looking at the future, we remember that most of the indicators of the SDGs are national indicators, are at the national level.

451
00:49:45,739 --> 00:49:50,982
[GRYNSPAN]: So is national governments the ones that have to drive this agenda?

452
00:49:51,462 --> 00:49:58,607
[GRYNSPAN]: And there, Marty, your question, because to drive this agenda at the national level, we need parliaments.

453
00:49:59,107 --> 00:50:07,217
[GRYNSPAN]: We need those that have the voice, have the laws in their hands to be able to partner with the government for this to happen.

454
00:50:07,518 --> 00:50:09,160
[GRYNSPAN]: And the UN has to be there.

455
00:50:09,180 --> 00:50:14,686
[GRYNSPAN]: You know, I've been in the UN long enough to know

456
00:50:15,859 --> 00:50:20,722
[GRYNSPAN]: that we have to defend it, because I believe in the UN, but also the things that have to change.

457
00:50:21,343 --> 00:50:25,586
[GRYNSPAN]: We are still very supply-driven with the countries.

458
00:50:26,066 --> 00:50:32,851
[GRYNSPAN]: We need to be much more demand-driven to be able to help the countries in achieving the SDGs.

459
00:50:33,311 --> 00:50:45,174
[GRYNSPAN]: It won't only happen because we take an account of who has gotten who is on the way to the SDGs and who is not.

460
00:50:45,654 --> 00:50:58,597
[GRYNSPAN]: We need to put back our effort at the country level so we can really make the SDGs go farther towards 2030.

461
00:50:58,737 --> 00:50:59,317
[SPEAKER_06]: All right.

462
00:50:59,377 --> 00:51:03,178
[SPEAKER_06]: Maria Spinoza, SG's got to be an advocate for the SDGs.

463
00:51:04,619 --> 00:51:12,046
[ESPINOSA]: Well, I think the SDGs are the right ambition, the right roadmap, the right shared narrative.

464
00:51:12,527 --> 00:51:15,930
[ESPINOSA]: They have been extremely important in pushing the development agenda.

465
00:51:17,451 --> 00:51:20,654
[ESPINOSA]: But the problem is that ambition is not action.

466
00:51:21,678 --> 00:51:24,720
[ESPINOSA]: Ambition does not transform people's lives on the ground.

467
00:51:25,060 --> 00:51:36,248
[ESPINOSA]: I'm also worried not only of the lack of development of the 18% targets on track, I'm also very worried about regression and stagnation.

468
00:51:37,108 --> 00:51:38,609
[ESPINOSA]: And what to do about that?

469
00:51:39,030 --> 00:51:43,513
[ESPINOSA]: First of all, I strongly believe that development cannot be delivered from New York.

470
00:51:44,348 --> 00:51:48,333
[ESPINOSA]: That's absolutely something that we need to learn.

471
00:51:48,933 --> 00:51:51,356
[ESPINOSA]: Number two, I agree with Rebecca.

472
00:51:51,857 --> 00:51:57,623
[ESPINOSA]: Development needs to be nationally owned, funded,

473
00:51:59,992 --> 00:52:11,096
[ESPINOSA]: supported in the role of the UN here, and particularly of the Secretary General, is to help countries to deliver their development pathways.

474
00:52:11,716 --> 00:52:23,081
[ESPINOSA]: But of course, there are direct actions, but there are also what we call the structural hurdles of development.

475
00:52:23,421 --> 00:52:24,782
[ESPINOSA]: The UN can help there.

476
00:52:25,462 --> 00:52:31,865
[ESPINOSA]: For example, to ensure that there is a profound reform of international financial architecture.

477
00:52:32,145 --> 00:52:35,446
[ESPINOSA]: The UN is not a bank, but it's a convener.

478
00:52:35,867 --> 00:52:43,110
[ESPINOSA]: It has the data, it has the information, it can provide the advice, the space for multilateral banks to come together.

479
00:52:43,910 --> 00:52:45,792
[ESPINOSA]: and to have that conversation.

480
00:52:46,592 --> 00:52:51,856
[ESPINOSA]: We saw it with a very strong outcome of the Sevilla commitment.

481
00:52:52,437 --> 00:52:59,582
[ESPINOSA]: And I think we cannot wait until 2030, the last day, to start thinking about the future.

482
00:53:00,062 --> 00:53:12,085
[ESPINOSA]: As Secretary General, I will work hand by hand with member states to imagine a development era that is nationally owned with the three things that developing countries need.

483
00:53:12,325 --> 00:53:15,866
[ESPINOSA]: Money and resources, technology and institutional capacity.

484
00:53:15,926 --> 00:53:16,407
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

485
00:53:16,687 --> 00:53:17,607
[SPEAKER_06]: Michelle Bachelet.

486
00:53:17,927 --> 00:53:27,175
[BACHELET]: Well, yes, I think sometimes we think on development that we have a problem with money, with resources, and it's true, but it's not that there's not enough global wealth.

487
00:53:27,575 --> 00:53:38,644
[BACHELET]: I mean, there's $430 billion a year as a wealth, and the gap on financing for development is $4.3 trillion.

488
00:53:40,065 --> 00:53:40,505
[BACHELET]: every year.

489
00:53:40,966 --> 00:53:48,769
[BACHELET]: So there are resources, and those resources can come with all the different areas that we have already spoke now and before.

490
00:53:49,270 --> 00:54:00,295
[BACHELET]: Of course, the international financial institution, and I agree, they need to be reformed because they were created in a different area with different challenges.

491
00:54:00,695 --> 00:54:08,839
[BACHELET]: And now we need those institutions, and not only the World Bank and the IMF, the whole group of the IDB, the Asian development,

492
00:54:09,219 --> 00:54:15,145
[BACHELET]: the African Development Bank, all to work together with the private sector as well, because many of these things are really important.

493
00:54:15,705 --> 00:54:21,311
[BACHELET]: If we don't have development, if we fail with developing countries, we're failing to the people.

494
00:54:21,831 --> 00:54:25,275
[BACHELET]: And we are failing to our aspiration of peace and security.

495
00:54:25,675 --> 00:54:30,580
[BACHELET]: We're failing to our aspiration also of ensuring people their human rights.

496
00:54:31,020 --> 00:54:33,643
[BACHELET]: So development needs to be owned, nationally owned.

497
00:54:34,123 --> 00:54:48,864
[BACHELET]: And in that sense, but not only by state members, because having been a president, what I saw, that when you have a policy, policies that last and not become completely evaporated when the next election comes, is when

498
00:54:49,685 --> 00:54:51,707
[BACHELET]: Legislature owns it as well.

499
00:54:52,127 --> 00:55:09,882
[BACHELET]: So Parliament, Martin, are really essential, because we need parliamentarians to own development and own those goals, and to be part of that, and to ensure that the laws can, I would say, reflect what is needed to ensure all these possibilities.

500
00:55:11,101 --> 00:55:13,142
[BACHELET]: Today there's a discussion of what will come in the future.

501
00:55:13,863 --> 00:55:18,466
[BACHELET]: Some people say that next year the UN will be discussing the next step.

502
00:55:19,186 --> 00:55:22,608
[BACHELET]: And I think the next step probably will have to think about it very seriously.

503
00:55:23,168 --> 00:55:28,492
[BACHELET]: Fewer promises, but promises that you can ensure that will be solved, that will be funded.

504
00:55:28,972 --> 00:55:30,253
[BACHELET]: and that you will defend it.

505
00:55:30,753 --> 00:55:33,815
[BACHELET]: Because I think what people want is that their lives improve.

506
00:55:34,236 --> 00:55:34,776
[BACHELET]: And that's it.

507
00:55:34,856 --> 00:55:40,100
[BACHELET]: Not to have hundreds and hundreds of, you know, goals, but goals who really can improve people's lives.

508
00:55:40,500 --> 00:55:45,183
[BACHELET]: Goals that really can ensure that children can go to school, that go to the clinic.

509
00:55:45,463 --> 00:55:48,464
[BACHELET]: that women can have children in a clinic.

510
00:55:48,864 --> 00:55:51,725
[BACHELET]: Those are the things that people want in their daily life.

511
00:55:51,765 --> 00:55:59,668
[BACHELET]: And that's what I think that one of the things that women can bring to this role as well is more humanism.

512
00:56:00,209 --> 00:56:02,129
[BACHELET]: Because I believe we need more humanism.

513
00:56:02,549 --> 00:56:03,530
[BACHELET]: And people need hope.

514
00:56:09,792 --> 00:56:17,759
[SPEAKER_06]: It's interesting, and you mentioned peace and security as several of you have, and I think on this question of, you know, but all of you said there is the money.

515
00:56:17,779 --> 00:56:33,732
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm always struck by that one figure that obviously conflict is a big driver of a lack of development, and the UN's global peacekeeping budget is $5.38 billion, which is equivalent to 16 hours of global military expenditure.

516
00:56:34,272 --> 00:56:39,355
[SPEAKER_06]: So when you say it's a question of priorities and where you put your money, it's very interesting.

517
00:56:39,375 --> 00:56:44,999
[SPEAKER_06]: We didn't talk about peacekeeping, but of course, that's a very important role that the UN does.

518
00:56:45,359 --> 00:56:53,384
[SPEAKER_06]: So we've now got a compound question about two sort of related topics on science, technology, and AI.

519
00:56:53,884 --> 00:56:59,888
[SPEAKER_06]: First of all, from Robert Dygraf, who is president-elect of the International Science Council.

520
00:57:00,428 --> 00:57:01,629
[SPEAKER_06]: Your question, please.

521
00:57:02,249 --> 00:57:08,331
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, thank you so much for creating a place for science and technology in this very interesting debate.

522
00:57:09,011 --> 00:57:16,734
[SPEAKER_05]: It's clear in the future, science will be more important to address global challenges, and it can be a source of optimism.

523
00:57:17,314 --> 00:57:28,798
[SPEAKER_05]: So what are your ideas to make the role of science in the UN more stronger, more structural, in particular, more equitable, in a sense of engaging all member states

524
00:57:29,318 --> 00:57:37,006
[SPEAKER_05]: in terms of gender equality, but also in terms of listening to the voice of the next generation, like my colleague here.

525
00:57:37,186 --> 00:57:37,747
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, thank you.

526
00:57:37,767 --> 00:57:46,636
[SPEAKER_06]: If you could hand the microphone, in fact, to Tatuli Khedesheli, who is an IE University student who wants to explore the topic of AI.

527
00:57:46,956 --> 00:57:47,217
[SPEAKER_06]: Go ahead.

528
00:57:47,237 --> 00:57:47,877
[SPEAKER_02]: Good afternoon.

529
00:57:48,037 --> 00:57:49,139
[SPEAKER_02]: It is an honor to be here.

530
00:57:49,379 --> 00:57:50,740
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you for sharing your insights.

531
00:57:51,661 --> 00:57:55,748
[SPEAKER_02]: Emerging technologies and artificial intelligence are transforming societies globally.

532
00:57:56,149 --> 00:58:02,981
[SPEAKER_02]: Yet, many of the most important decisions about these technologies are made by a small number of states and private companies.

533
00:58:03,918 --> 00:58:12,443
[SPEAKER_02]: What role should the United Nations play in ensuring that all countries have a meaningful voice in shaping the rules that govern emerging technologies?

534
00:58:12,803 --> 00:58:13,223
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

535
00:58:13,323 --> 00:58:17,986
[SPEAKER_06]: OK, so you've got two minutes, candidates, to answer both those questions.

536
00:58:18,026 --> 00:58:19,406
[SPEAKER_06]: Maria, you kick off.

537
00:58:19,647 --> 00:58:20,007
[ESPINOSA]: Thank you.

538
00:58:20,087 --> 00:58:20,627
[GRYNSPAN]: Why me?

539
00:58:20,687 --> 00:58:21,027
[GRYNSPAN]: Why me?

540
00:58:21,047 --> 00:58:21,628
[GRYNSPAN]: Yeah, well.

541
00:58:22,568 --> 00:58:26,169
[ESPINOSA]: Well, first of all, the role of science, absolutely vital.

542
00:58:26,649 --> 00:58:45,356
[ESPINOSA]: But I think the UN has the science capacity scattered in many places, and I think that we really need to make sure that there is a space and place for coherent use and organized use of science into decision making.

543
00:58:45,616 --> 00:58:51,518
[ESPINOSA]: How is that you build in science into daily decision making within the UN system?

544
00:58:51,898 --> 00:58:58,843
[ESPINOSA]: Second, on AI, I think artificial intelligence is not a tech issue alone.

545
00:58:59,443 --> 00:59:00,624
[ESPINOSA]: It is a jobs issue.

546
00:59:01,004 --> 00:59:02,385
[ESPINOSA]: It is an economic issue.

547
00:59:02,525 --> 00:59:03,686
[ESPINOSA]: It's a security issue.

548
00:59:03,786 --> 00:59:04,907
[ESPINOSA]: It's an ethics issue.

549
00:59:05,488 --> 00:59:10,451
[ESPINOSA]: And the UN is perhaps the best place to deal with the complexity of AI.

550
00:59:10,871 --> 00:59:17,954
[ESPINOSA]: which is really having an impact in our lives today but in our lives in the future.

551
00:59:18,374 --> 00:59:23,696
[ESPINOSA]: We have come with the global digital compact that was agreed by all member states.

552
00:59:23,816 --> 00:59:31,219
[ESPINOSA]: We are now about to have in July here in Geneva the first global dialogue on artificial intelligence governance.

553
00:59:31,739 --> 00:59:40,589
[ESPINOSA]: I think that there is a very important role for the UN to bring all the parties to the conversation.

554
00:59:41,050 --> 00:59:53,183
[ESPINOSA]: An inclusive dialogue, perhaps not to prescribe, but to ensure that the use of artificial intelligence is human-centered, is ethical, and for the common good.

555
00:59:53,563 --> 00:59:59,726
[ESPINOSA]: Actually, I think the dialogue taking place here in July is called Artificial Intelligence for Good.

556
01:00:00,007 --> 01:00:03,088
[ESPINOSA]: I think that is the collective responsibility that we all have.

557
01:00:03,429 --> 01:00:16,456
[ESPINOSA]: So, of course, the private sector, the UN should not stop innovation, of course, but the UN should bring and use its convening power to have everybody at the table, especially the younger generation.

558
01:00:16,496 --> 01:00:16,856
[ESPINOSA]: All right.

559
01:00:17,016 --> 01:00:17,836
[BACHELET]: Michelle Bachelet?

560
01:00:18,157 --> 01:00:19,177
[BACHELET]: Well, I'm a physician.

561
01:00:19,757 --> 01:00:20,478
[BACHELET]: So, for me,

562
01:00:21,618 --> 01:00:27,100
[BACHELET]: I always used science-based evidence to try to understand better.

563
01:00:28,041 --> 01:00:35,603
[BACHELET]: And I also tried to think, and that's why also looking after the root causes of what we're looking at, to try to find the best solutions.

564
01:00:35,983 --> 01:00:38,484
[BACHELET]: So I believe science plays a substantial role.

565
01:00:38,924 --> 01:00:42,106
[BACHELET]: I mean, we have seen it, for example, in the response to COVID, of course.

566
01:00:42,126 --> 01:00:43,326
[BACHELET]: That was really important.

567
01:00:43,346 --> 01:00:47,808
[BACHELET]: And the good thing is that the scientific sector probably was the only sector, from the beginning,

568
01:00:49,028 --> 01:00:56,996
[BACHELET]: that was work with solidarity, that they exchange the information, the DNAs that could be brought up to the vaccine.

569
01:00:57,016 --> 01:01:00,500
[BACHELET]: So I really believe that science has to play a role on climate change.

570
01:01:00,860 --> 01:01:05,425
[BACHELET]: Science also has so much to say how things are going if we have to change.

571
01:01:05,645 --> 01:01:11,831
[BACHELET]: On the issue of AI, as High Commissioner of Human Rights, we work a lot with Silicon Valley and with all the companies.

572
01:01:12,452 --> 01:01:18,814
[BACHELET]: trying to understand that AI is essential, is a part of our lives in the future.

573
01:01:19,314 --> 01:01:24,016
[BACHELET]: It has so many beneficial issues, but at the same time, a lot of challenges.

574
01:01:24,436 --> 01:01:30,138
[BACHELET]: In human rights in particular, we had a lot of challenges in the use of artificial intelligence and others to

575
01:01:31,358 --> 01:01:33,881
[BACHELET]: I would say go after some human rights defenders, etc.

576
01:01:33,921 --> 01:01:35,822
[BACHELET]: So we work with the companies.

577
01:01:35,882 --> 01:01:46,172
[BACHELET]: I think the work with the companies to ensure that the human rights perspective is included from the beginning, not after they have created a product and then realize that it's bad for the human being.

578
01:01:46,392 --> 01:01:49,034
[BACHELET]: And lastly, I also think that

579
01:01:50,035 --> 01:01:52,997
[BACHELET]: We need to ensure that AI, that's what the UN has to do.

580
01:01:53,578 --> 01:01:55,579
[BACHELET]: It's a convening power to sit together.

581
01:01:55,619 --> 01:02:01,603
[BACHELET]: I mean, it's the only place, I mean, something that companies don't have is a table of 193 member states.

582
01:02:02,003 --> 01:02:15,353
[BACHELET]: So we can sit together all these stakeholders with the 193 member state to ensure that if AI continues, and it's important, and it will, that doesn't mean that the same group of countries will be left behind.

583
01:02:16,433 --> 01:02:17,234
[BACHELET]: Rebecca Greenspan.

584
01:02:17,816 --> 01:02:21,579
[GRYNSPAN]: Yes, I think that we have to learn a lot from climate change.

585
01:02:21,859 --> 01:02:32,007
[GRYNSPAN]: It was when we brought the science and the scientific community into the collective discussion that we could advance climate change.

586
01:02:32,067 --> 01:02:43,055
[GRYNSPAN]: And I think that is very important, the AI advisory committee and the scientific committee that has been established by the secretary general and the digital compact.

587
01:02:43,615 --> 01:02:52,243
[GRYNSPAN]: And I think that that mirrors how important this could be, because we cannot think or discuss something we don't understand.

588
01:02:52,884 --> 01:03:00,190
[GRYNSPAN]: And to understand, we need to bring the scientific community into the discussion with all the other stakeholders.

589
01:03:00,230 --> 01:03:04,815
[GRYNSPAN]: So very important, the advisory committee and the scientific committee on this area.

590
01:03:05,295 --> 01:03:10,678
[GRYNSPAN]: With respect to AI, I would say three very quick points.

591
01:03:10,878 --> 01:03:14,000
[GRYNSPAN]: First, the principles for ethical behavior.

592
01:03:14,460 --> 01:03:16,081
[GRYNSPAN]: And the UN has worked on this.

593
01:03:16,201 --> 01:03:17,641
[GRYNSPAN]: UNESCO has worked on this.

594
01:03:18,062 --> 01:03:22,924
[GRYNSPAN]: And there are principles and soft laws that are there that we have to implement.

595
01:03:23,384 --> 01:03:27,446
[GRYNSPAN]: And I think that Michelle is right that it has to be considered from the beginning.

596
01:03:27,867 --> 01:03:34,470
[GRYNSPAN]: I remember one of the fathers of AI saying that if you don't consider the

597
01:03:34,730 --> 01:03:39,494
[GRYNSPAN]: ethics from the beginning of the algorithm, then you won't be able to regulate it.

598
01:03:39,614 --> 01:03:40,935
[GRYNSPAN]: So principles.

599
01:03:41,595 --> 01:03:42,876
[GRYNSPAN]: Second, development.

600
01:03:43,116 --> 01:03:45,358
[GRYNSPAN]: We have to close the digital divide.

601
01:03:45,838 --> 01:03:51,202
[GRYNSPAN]: And so development is very important here to be able to go farther.

602
01:03:51,662 --> 01:03:53,644
[GRYNSPAN]: And I have my last point.

603
01:03:53,784 --> 01:03:57,606
[GRYNSPAN]: My last point is the cooperation in the UN for the future.

604
01:03:57,667 --> 01:04:02,110
[GRYNSPAN]: There are three very difficult areas that we will have to discuss.

605
01:04:02,850 --> 01:04:08,734
[GRYNSPAN]: information, cyber security, and the autonomous lethal weapons.

606
01:04:08,935 --> 01:04:16,840
[GRYNSPAN]: Those are difficult areas, and we have to see how we bring all the actors to be able to start a constructive conversation.

607
01:04:16,860 --> 01:04:21,864
[SPEAKER_06]: I'd like to leave enough time for your closing statements, which at this stage are only going to be about 90 seconds.

608
01:04:21,964 --> 01:04:24,005
[SPEAKER_06]: Our final question from the audience, please.

609
01:04:24,366 --> 01:04:27,408
[SPEAKER_06]: Marie Lausalle, director of the Geneva Graduate Institute.

610
01:04:27,428 --> 01:04:29,049
[SPEAKER_06]: You've got a question on human rights.

611
01:04:30,342 --> 01:04:34,003
[SPEAKER_03]: Congratulations first to the three of you for stepping up to the challenge.

612
01:04:34,663 --> 01:04:42,446
[SPEAKER_03]: In 1957, UN Secretary-General Di Amishold emphasized that, and I quote, without recognition of human rights, we shall never have peace.

613
01:04:43,006 --> 01:04:47,327
[SPEAKER_03]: As Secretary-General, what will be your approach to the issue of human rights?

614
01:04:47,867 --> 01:04:52,429
[SPEAKER_03]: Will you be a champion for the principles that are enshrined in the UN Declaration of Human Rights?

615
01:04:53,129 --> 01:04:56,990
[BACHELET]: Michel Bachelet as a former human rights commissioner.

616
01:04:57,490 --> 01:05:02,852
[BACHELET]: It was funny because we decided who will start and I received this fantastic award.

617
01:05:02,872 --> 01:05:04,213
[BACHELET]: Yes, very appropriate.

618
01:05:04,333 --> 01:05:17,777
[BACHELET]: Well, I do believe, really I do believe and I'm concerned listening to some countries that if we don't have, if we don't respect human rights and we don't have development and we don't, we will never have peace and security, never.

619
01:05:18,817 --> 01:05:21,319
[BACHELET]: They're so interconnected and so intertwined.

620
01:05:21,799 --> 01:05:34,286
[BACHELET]: So if I'm Secretary General, what I would try to do is to include human rights perspectives in all the areas that we need to work as UN, because that's the only way that you can build on that.

621
01:05:36,427 --> 01:05:52,626
[BACHELET]: You also have to think on the whole machinery, not only the UN machinery, because what you need also is national commission of UN rights that do their job, judiciary that not threatened because they are intimidated, civil society that can speak out.

622
01:05:53,106 --> 01:05:54,287
[BACHELET]: because they don't feel fear.

623
01:05:54,847 --> 01:06:07,415
[BACHELET]: And also, finally, journalists that can really speak out when things are happening, because when you have all those institutions functioning, we need the UN, the Office of the High Commissioner, to work and have funded.

624
01:06:07,495 --> 01:06:12,858
[BACHELET]: It's only 4% of all the funds that they receive, so it's not much, and it needs to be supported.

625
01:06:13,358 --> 01:06:18,722
[BACHELET]: But we need also the whole structure to function, because we need, when institutions work,

626
01:06:19,422 --> 01:06:21,124
[BACHELET]: People consider it.

627
01:06:21,364 --> 01:06:24,707
[BACHELET]: People can prevent violations from happening.

628
01:06:25,188 --> 01:06:30,433
[BACHELET]: So I think a lot of things need to be done, but I'm sure they have to be all over the place, if I have to say.

629
01:06:30,493 --> 01:06:35,137
[BACHELET]: Human rights has to be at the center of how we look at peace and security development as well.

630
01:06:36,138 --> 01:06:48,405
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm going to ask you all the same thing, just as an adjunct, because we've seen a real retreat on sexual and reproductive health rights, which particularly affects women, and issues of gender, sexual identity have become quite politicised.

631
01:06:48,445 --> 01:06:56,030
[SPEAKER_06]: So how would you all tackle that, if I could add that question as well, but very quickly, if you could answer that particular point, Michelle Bachelet.

632
01:06:57,768 --> 01:07:04,952
[BACHELET]: not giving up, not giving up insistent and putting the women's agenda at the more important place.

633
01:07:05,293 --> 01:07:05,733
[BACHELET]: That's it.

634
01:07:06,253 --> 01:07:07,514
[BACHELET]: And there's lots of strategies.

635
01:07:07,894 --> 01:07:10,076
[BACHELET]: But the first thing is that we won't give up.

636
01:07:10,216 --> 01:07:12,797
[BACHELET]: We won't accept that backlash.

637
01:07:13,378 --> 01:07:14,618
[SPEAKER_06]: OK. Rebecca Greenspan.

638
01:07:15,159 --> 01:07:17,840
[GRYNSPAN]: Let me add, human rights is not a menu.

639
01:07:18,561 --> 01:07:20,302
[GRYNSPAN]: It's a package.

640
01:07:20,402 --> 01:07:22,163
[GRYNSPAN]: We have to comply with all of that.

641
01:07:23,470 --> 01:07:30,358
[GRYNSPAN]: And the countries have a responsibility to comply with human rights, with international law, and with humanitarian law.

642
01:07:31,079 --> 01:07:37,146
[GRYNSPAN]: I think that we need to push back again on the politicization of human rights and humanitarian law.

643
01:07:37,927 --> 01:07:39,328
[GRYNSPAN]: We fought so hard

644
01:07:40,009 --> 01:07:46,936
[GRYNSPAN]: for these areas to be out of politics and to be only centered on the human needs of people.

645
01:07:47,296 --> 01:07:53,562
[GRYNSPAN]: Precisely that's what humanitarian law is, what human rights is, is not to discriminate between anybody.

646
01:07:54,022 --> 01:08:05,173
[GRYNSPAN]: I think that we need the voice of everybody to push back again on the politicization of international law, of humanitarian law, and of the principles of human rights.

647
01:08:05,845 --> 01:08:20,478
[GRYNSPAN]: Second, in the UN-80 process, a group for human rights was formed in the UN precisely for systematize and have a dialogue between all the systems on human rights.

648
01:08:20,699 --> 01:08:21,900
[GRYNSPAN]: I think that is a good idea.

649
01:08:22,500 --> 01:08:33,367
[GRYNSPAN]: So as Secretary General, I will try to resource that group properly, because many times human rights is not properly resourced.

650
01:08:33,848 --> 01:08:44,295
[GRYNSPAN]: I will try for this to be effective in the objectives and not fall into it being another bureaucratic layer of, you know, process.

651
01:08:44,815 --> 01:08:46,957
[GRYNSPAN]: So let's try to make this work.

652
01:08:46,997 --> 01:08:57,508
[GRYNSPAN]: I think that there are good ideas out there and that as Secretary General, I will support it for it to be effective in the objectives that we are set for ourselves.

653
01:08:57,528 --> 01:08:58,409
[GRYNSPAN]: Maria Espinoza.

654
01:08:59,990 --> 01:09:00,511
[SPEAKER_06]: Human rights.

655
01:09:01,540 --> 01:09:05,761
[ESPINOSA]: Well, it's very easy to say, oh yes, I will be a champion on human rights.

656
01:09:06,041 --> 01:09:09,942
[ESPINOSA]: Very easy to say, difficult to do when you look at the UN.

657
01:09:10,002 --> 01:09:13,843
[ESPINOSA]: When I serve here as ambassador, I serve at the Human Rights Council.

658
01:09:14,463 --> 01:09:20,545
[ESPINOSA]: I saw the potential that the human rights architecture has because we have created it, no, collectively.

659
01:09:21,605 --> 01:09:30,311
[ESPINOSA]: I saw the potential to ensure that human rights were used for prevention, for peace, for development.

660
01:09:31,332 --> 01:09:39,958
[ESPINOSA]: I understood that universality, non-politization, the undivisible nature of human rights were extremely important.

661
01:09:40,378 --> 01:09:49,185
[ESPINOSA]: But I also saw what were the tensions among member states, duplication with the work of human rights in New York.

662
01:09:50,025 --> 01:10:00,776
[ESPINOSA]: the lack of coherence of the work, mandates multiplying, and we know that is the pillar that is chronically underfunded in the system.

663
01:10:01,156 --> 01:10:02,377
[ESPINOSA]: So what to do?

664
01:10:02,517 --> 01:10:03,378
[ESPINOSA]: That's the question.

665
01:10:04,019 --> 01:10:09,864
[ESPINOSA]: I would say that 20 years of the Human Rights Council, this very year,

666
01:10:10,525 --> 01:10:24,452
[ESPINOSA]: Perhaps it is time that we rethink how is that we have built this very complex human rights architecture, because everything the UN does needs to have human dignity at the centre.

667
01:10:24,692 --> 01:10:27,114
[SPEAKER_06]: And this is through sexual reproductive health rights?

668
01:10:27,134 --> 01:10:29,475
[ESPINOSA]: Well, and of course, absolutely.

669
01:10:30,616 --> 01:10:36,279
[ESPINOSA]: I also looked at the UNAT process and the proposal for a human rights group.

670
01:10:36,419 --> 01:10:38,620
[ESPINOSA]: I think it's a good initiative.

671
01:10:39,697 --> 01:10:47,222
[ESPINOSA]: only if it's fully deployed to ensure that the UN delivers on human rights as one.

672
01:10:47,782 --> 01:10:59,509
[ESPINOSA]: There is no competition, there is no duplication, there is a system working together to ensure, and I say again, that the human dignity is at the centre of everything we do.

673
01:10:59,529 --> 01:11:01,811
[SPEAKER_06]: And the central reproductive health rights, would you

674
01:11:02,896 --> 01:11:05,157
[SPEAKER_06]: The other two answered that, how would you answer it?

675
01:11:05,777 --> 01:11:08,938
[ESPINOSA]: Well, this is part of the package, I agree.

676
01:11:09,638 --> 01:11:19,881
[ESPINOSA]: Human rights are indivisible, economic and social rights, political and civil rights, they all come together.

677
01:11:20,001 --> 01:11:28,104
[ESPINOSA]: It is a complex package, but we need to do something about it to ensure that the system we have created is well-funded,

678
01:11:28,544 --> 01:11:30,465
[SPEAKER_06]: operate well and serve humanity.

679
01:11:30,525 --> 01:11:57,883
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you to all our questions and now going to up the tempo because we have our closing statements and in the interest of transparency to determine the order I've got this little bag here and I'm going to be pulling up we did that also at the beginning where people would be seated who would go first and so on so the first 90 seconds max two minutes I shall be the time police first to go to the stage is Maria Fernanda Espinoza so your time will start when you get to the stage

680
01:11:58,244 --> 01:11:58,746
[SPEAKER_06]: Better hurry.

681
01:11:59,127 --> 01:11:59,488
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

682
01:12:06,092 --> 01:12:06,912
[ESPINOSA]: Thank you, thank you.

683
01:12:06,952 --> 01:12:10,493
[ESPINOSA]: I think it speaks volume to see this room absolutely packed.

684
01:12:10,693 --> 01:12:12,793
[ESPINOSA]: The interest of the UN remains there.

685
01:12:13,393 --> 01:12:19,795
[ESPINOSA]: Excellencies, colleagues, and friends, there is no doubt that we live in a world in fire.

686
01:12:20,555 --> 01:12:31,257
[ESPINOSA]: Wars multiplying, climate shocks accelerating, human rights are under strain, and most of all, trust in our institutions is fading.

687
01:12:31,957 --> 01:12:38,458
[ESPINOSA]: There are vast problems, but I think we all know that the answer cannot be a collection of band-aids.

688
01:12:38,998 --> 01:12:44,519
[ESPINOSA]: It cannot be just another report or another committee or another slogan.

689
01:12:45,139 --> 01:12:51,001
[ESPINOSA]: The crisis that the UN faces today requires something bolder than a chief administrator.

690
01:12:51,721 --> 01:12:58,362
[ESPINOSA]: It needs a peacemaker, a top manager, a strong advocate for international law and the UN Charter.

691
01:12:59,082 --> 01:13:03,546
[ESPINOSA]: I think this moment calls for a renaissance, Secretary General.

692
01:13:04,446 --> 01:13:08,770
[ESPINOSA]: A Secretary General capable of restoring the UN's moral authority.

693
01:13:09,350 --> 01:13:18,057
[ESPINOSA]: A Secretary General capable of giving the world hope that a better and more peaceful world can be built if we act together.

694
01:13:18,657 --> 01:13:24,280
[ESPINOSA]: A vision where the UN acts before crisis explode through an effective early action hub.

695
01:13:24,820 --> 01:13:33,185
[ESPINOSA]: A vision where development is not measured by speeches or slogans, but by whether people have jobs, food, education, dignity.

696
01:13:33,985 --> 01:13:39,947
[ESPINOSA]: A vision where technology is shaped by and for humanity, not only by power or profit.

697
01:13:40,567 --> 01:13:52,472
[ESPINOSA]: I think at this moment we cannot afford a secretary general who simply manages the decline, but is brave enough and equipped enough to make the transformations the organization needs.

698
01:13:53,112 --> 01:14:02,459
[ESPINOSA]: We need a secretary general that can speak with courage, listen with humility, and bring countries back to a shared sense of purpose.

699
01:14:02,879 --> 01:14:06,822
[ESPINOSA]: That is the leadership, I believe, this moment requires.

700
01:14:07,182 --> 01:14:09,504
[ESPINOSA]: That is the leadership I will bring to the UN.

701
01:14:09,524 --> 01:14:09,884
[ESPINOSA]: Thank you.

702
01:14:09,964 --> 01:14:10,445
[ESPINOSA]: I thank you.

703
01:14:11,105 --> 01:14:19,191
[SPEAKER_06]: So, and the next, the next panelist to go up, Michel Bachelet.

704
01:14:24,690 --> 01:14:29,635
[BACHELET]: Well, the United Nations is not a perfect institution, and we know it very well, for the ones who have worked there.

705
01:14:30,316 --> 01:14:34,040
[BACHELET]: But even in perfect institutions, they can protect people.

706
01:14:35,161 --> 01:14:37,683
[BACHELET]: And when they fail, people pay the price.

707
01:14:38,504 --> 01:14:41,867
[BACHELET]: I'm not running for Secretary General to administer the President.

708
01:14:42,631 --> 01:14:47,094
[BACHELET]: I'm running to help build the United Nations that the next 80 years demand.

709
01:14:47,735 --> 01:14:48,916
[BACHELET]: And here's my commitment to you.

710
01:14:49,676 --> 01:14:56,662
[BACHELET]: I will defend multilateralism, not any multilateralism, but one firmly anchored in the principles and values of the UN Charter.

711
01:14:57,482 --> 01:15:00,505
[BACHELET]: I will be an independent Secretary General, always on the ground.

712
01:15:01,085 --> 01:15:07,050
[BACHELET]: When conflicts arise, I will be there, offering mediation, insisting on respect for international law.

713
01:15:07,790 --> 01:15:15,595
[BACHELET]: I will reform this organization to make it more agile, more efficient, more accountable, and I will do so through dialogue and building consensus.

714
01:15:16,095 --> 01:15:17,016
[BACHELET]: But let me be clear.

715
01:15:17,616 --> 01:15:22,499
[BACHELET]: No reform can come at the expense of the principles that define the institution.

716
01:15:23,100 --> 01:15:29,544
[BACHELET]: The pillars of peace and security, sustainable development and human rights are not adjustable, are not negotiable.

717
01:15:30,124 --> 01:15:34,327
[BACHELET]: Leadership means achieving difficult objectives while keeping them intact.

718
01:15:35,007 --> 01:15:39,670
[BACHELET]: My message of force is all for people throughout the world, to boys and especially girls.

719
01:15:40,291 --> 01:15:41,051
[BACHELET]: It is possible.

720
01:15:41,632 --> 01:15:52,600
[BACHELET]: With courage, with creativity, I place my experience and my commitment to principles at the service of the great task of becoming also the first woman ever to be Secretary General of the United Nations.

721
01:15:53,200 --> 01:15:55,322
[BACHELET]: And I will be honoured, deeply honoured by your trust.

722
01:15:56,002 --> 01:16:00,406
[BACHELET]: But let me say, I think to be First Secretary General,

723
01:16:01,086 --> 01:16:16,723
[BACHELET]: It would be worthy if one can bring to the table all countries, how we organize the Secretariat and the architecture, everyone that feels, because the 193 member states need to feel that the United Nations is theirs.

724
01:16:26,811 --> 01:16:28,051
[GRYNSPAN]: Well, hello, Geneva.

725
01:16:28,332 --> 01:16:30,612
[GRYNSPAN]: We didn't see that, say that before.

726
01:16:31,433 --> 01:16:32,473
[GRYNSPAN]: So let me start.

727
01:16:33,073 --> 01:16:36,174
[GRYNSPAN]: My parents were refugees of the Second World War.

728
01:16:36,995 --> 01:16:43,697
[GRYNSPAN]: A small country with no army took them in and treated them with respect and dignity.

729
01:16:44,397 --> 01:16:45,998
[GRYNSPAN]: I am the daughter of peace.

730
01:16:46,758 --> 01:16:52,440
[GRYNSPAN]: I know what worse takes away and what peace makes possible.

731
01:16:53,280 --> 01:17:00,462
[GRYNSPAN]: I am running because peace is in peril, and trust in the UN and international organizations is eroding.

732
01:17:01,102 --> 01:17:09,285
[GRYNSPAN]: We live in a very complex, multipolar world, with more conflicts today than in 1945.

733
01:17:09,765 --> 01:17:17,267
[GRYNSPAN]: We need a secretary-general that can build bridges, talk to all, negotiate with all, regardless.

734
01:17:18,427 --> 01:17:25,593
[GRYNSPAN]: But we also know that in this multipolarity, we need to choose.

735
01:17:25,934 --> 01:17:28,075
[GRYNSPAN]: Multipolarity is not a choice.

736
01:17:28,716 --> 01:17:29,356
[GRYNSPAN]: It's a fact.

737
01:17:30,057 --> 01:17:33,380
[GRYNSPAN]: What is a choice is multilateralism.

738
01:17:34,120 --> 01:17:40,366
[GRYNSPAN]: A world that is multipolar without multilateralism will drive us to fragmentation.

739
01:17:41,146 --> 01:17:52,442
[GRYNSPAN]: A world of multipolarity with multilateralism will allow us, holds the promise of decentralization and a better world.

740
01:17:52,803 --> 01:17:56,909
[GRYNSPAN]: And this is true not only for the small and medium-sized countries,

741
01:17:57,229 --> 01:18:01,313
[GRYNSPAN]: where our resilience comes from our interdependence.

742
01:18:01,854 --> 01:18:14,106
[GRYNSPAN]: It's also true for the big powers, because they were the ones that lost the most, fought the most, and died the most in the wars of the 20th century.

743
01:18:15,727 --> 01:18:20,450
[GRYNSPAN]: As I said earlier in this panel, we live in a skeptical age.

744
01:18:21,011 --> 01:18:22,772
[GRYNSPAN]: That skepticism is real.

745
01:18:23,212 --> 01:18:28,616
[GRYNSPAN]: I have heard it through the campaign trail, and we must listen.

746
01:18:29,057 --> 01:18:35,161
[GRYNSPAN]: So if I can ask one thing from you, it is not to give away your agency.

747
01:18:35,561 --> 01:18:41,005
[GRYNSPAN]: This moment in history, this race, is a choice, a real choice.

748
01:18:41,465 --> 01:18:44,688
[GRYNSPAN]: So yes, be critical, but choose.

749
01:18:45,749 --> 01:18:46,209
[GRYNSPAN]: Thank you.

750
01:18:46,951 --> 01:18:47,852
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you Rebecca.

751
01:18:50,295 --> 01:18:55,558
[SPEAKER_06]: So, that's it from this UN Secretary-General debate from the Maison de la Paix.

752
01:18:55,938 --> 01:19:00,841
[SPEAKER_06]: Will the next Secretary-General be one of these three candidates, or Raphael Grossi, or Macky Sal?

753
01:19:01,241 --> 01:19:06,283
[SPEAKER_06]: Or indeed, actually, it's entirely possible that some new names may emerge.

754
01:19:06,704 --> 01:19:13,507
[SPEAKER_06]: The General Assembly vote on the recommendation of the Security Council, we should know by the end of the year, is going to be a long summer candidates.

755
01:19:13,527 --> 01:19:18,470
[SPEAKER_06]: From me, Zain Abidari, and everybody else on the team here from Geneva, goodbye.

756
01:19:29,700 --> 01:19:30,120
Thank you.

757
01:19:51,312 --> 01:19:52,072
Thank you very much.

